## Summary Table of Key Differences

| Aspect                       | Catholic Bible                      | Protestant Bible                   |
|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| Old Testament Books          | 46                                | 39                               |
| New Testament Books          | 27                                | 27                               |
| Deuterocanonical Books       | Included (7 books + additions)    | Excluded (considered Apocrypha)  |
| Basis for Old Testament      | Septuagint and tradition          | Hebrew Bible (Tanakh)             |
| Theological Concerns         | Accepts doctrines like purgatory  | Rejects doctrines unsupported by Hebrew canon |
| Formal Canon Definition      | Council of Trent (1546)            | No formal council; based on Reformation principles |
| Luther’s Bible (1534)        | N/A                               | Deuterocanonical books placed separately as Apocrypha |

---

## Conclusion and Opinion

The Protestant Bible has fewer books primarily because the leaders of the Protestant Reformation, notably Martin Luther, chose to align the Old Testament canon with the Hebrew Bible, excluding the deuterocanonical books found in the Septuagint and accepted by the Catholic Church. This decision was influenced by both theological concerns—such as opposition to doctrines like purgatory—and a desire to return to what they considered the original scriptural tradition used by Jesus and the apostles.

It is important to note that the Catholic Church did not add these books during the Reformation; rather, it maintained the traditional canon that had been in use, which was formally affirmed at the Council of Trent. The Protestant canon reflects a different historical and theological trajectory, emphasizing the Hebrew canon's authority.

This nuanced understanding dispels the simplistic notion that Protestants arbitrarily removed books. Instead, it highlights the complex interplay of history, theology, and tradition in shaping the biblical canon as recognized by different Christian communities.

